context: As of 2008[update], <b5_0>Germany<b5_0/> is the <a0_0>fourth largest<a0_0/> music market in the world and has exerted a strong influence on Dance and Rock music, and pioneered <a1_0><b6_0>trance<b6_0/><a1_0/> music. Artists such as Herbert Grönemeyer, Scorpions, Rammstein, Nena, Dieter Bohlen, Tokio Hotel and Modern Talking have enjoyed international fame. German musicians and, particularly, the pioneering bands Tangerine Dream and Kraftwerk have also contributed to the development of <a2_0>electronic<a2_0/> music. Germany hosts many large rock music festivals annually. The <a3_0><b7_0>Rock am Ring<a3_0/> festival<b7_0/> is the largest music festival in Germany, and among the largest in the world. <b8_0>German artists<b8_0/> also make up a large percentage of Industrial music acts, which is called Neue Deutsche Härte. Germany hosts some of the largest Goth scenes and festivals in the entire world, with events like Wave-Gothic-Treffen and M'era Luna Festival easily attracting <a4_0>up to 30,000<a4_0/> people. Amongst Germany's famous artists there are various Dutch entertainers, such as Johannes Heesters.
